{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:21:41.064277", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content=\"Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos EBGP lab\\nDate: (now)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Control-plane (FRR/BGP) appears healthy: all leaf/spine/super-spine routers have BGP routes for the /24 host prefixes and inter-router /31 links are up.\\n- Data-plane anomaly localized to the host layer: pc_0_0 is misconfigured with the wrong IP (10.0.1.2), creating a duplicate /24 address with pc_0_1. This causes pc_0_0 to be unreachable from its directly-attached leaf (leaf_router_0_0) and creates address duplication across the fabric.\\n- Root cause: host configuration error (pc_0_0 assigned 10.0.1.2 and default gateway 10.0.1.1 instead of being in its leaf's subnet 10.0.0.0/24). Routers and BGP are operating normally and are forwarding based on correct advertisements, which produces the observed mis-delivery/timeout behavior.\\n\\nObserved symptoms and key facts (evidence)\\n1. Duplicate host IPs\\n   - pc_0_0 ifconfig: inet 10.0.1.2/24\\n   - pc_0_1 ifconfig: inet 10.0.1.2/24\\n   - The global reachability aggregator mapped both hosts to the same IP (10.0.1.2).\\n\\n2. Host-level reachability\\n   - reachability tool: pc_0_0 <-> pc_0_1 pings show 0% loss (the test used IP 10.0.1.2 for both endpoints), indicating that traffic to 10.0.1.2 is answered somewhere on the fabric.\\n   - Direct router-to-host tests:\\n     - leaf_router_0_1 -> pc_0_1: ping succeeds (4/4).\\n     - leaf_router_0_0 -> pc_0_0: ping timed out.\\n\\n3. Router interfaces and connected networks\\n   - leaf_router_0_0 eth2: inet 10.0.0.1/24 (connected network 10.0.0.0/24)\\n   - leaf_router_0_1 eth2: inet 10.0.1.1/24 (connected network 10.0.1.0/24)\\n   - pc_0_0 is physically attached to leaf_router_0_0, but uses 10.0.1.2/24 (mismatch).\\n   - pc_0_1 is attached to leaf_router_0_1 and uses 10.0.1.2/24 (correct for that leaf).\\n\\n4. ARP/Neighbor state on leaf_router_0_0\\n   - ip neigh on leaf_router_0_0 shows entries for adjacent spine addresses (172.16.0.4, 172.16.0.8), but no ARP for the host IP 10.0.1.2 on eth2 — confirming leaf_router_0_0 is not seeing/responding to that host at L2/L3 on its eth2.\\n\\n5. BGP / routing tables (control-plane)\\n   - Each leaf/router has BGP entries for both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24. Example:\\n     - leaf_router_0_0 BGP table shows 10.0.0.0/24 locally originated and has a BGP route to 10.0.1.0/24 via a spine (172.16.0.4).\\n     - Super-spine and spines reflect both /24s; next-hops and AS-paths are as expected.\\n   - Router RIBs/FIBs show routes to the /24s and forwarding behavior is consistent with BGP advertisements (i.e., traffic to 10.0.1.0/24 will be forwarded towards leaf_router_0_1).\\n\\nDiagnosis / localization\\n- Primary faulty device: pc_0_0\\n  - Misconfigured IP address: 10.0.1.2/24 (should be in 10.0.0.0/24 to match leaf_router_0_0 eth2).\\n  - Default gateway on pc_0_0 is set to 10.0.1.1 (per its route table), which is not on the same LAN segment as its NIC to leaf_router_0_0.\\n- Secondary symptom: duplicate IP (10.0.1.2) exists on pc_0_1 (correct for its pod), causing an IP conflict across two different leaf switches.\\n- Network-level devices (leafs, spines, super-spine) — no evidence of failure:\\n  - Interfaces show UP state and correct /31 addressing on inter-router links.\\n  - BGP neighbors and route propagation are present for the expected prefixes.\\n  - No missing routes for the two /24s; control plane consistent.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis (why the symptoms occur)\\n- The host pc_0_0 is assigned an IP (10.0.1.2/24) that belongs to another leaf (leaf_router_0_1's 10.0.1.0/24). Because the host is physically connected to leaf_router_0_0 (whose interface is 10.0.0.1/24), the leaf does not ARP for 10.0.1.2 on its local interface and instead forwards packets for 10.0.1.2 into the fabric according to BGP (toward the owner of 10.0.1.0/24, which is leaf_router_0_1). Consequently:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 -> pc_0_0 pings fail because the router will forward traffic for 10.0.1.2 via BGP to leaf_router_0_1 (not onto the directly-connected interface), so the directly-attached host does not receive/answer them.\\n  - Traffic destined to 10.0.1.2 from elsewhere on the fabric may reach pc_0_1 (the correct owner of that prefix) or create ambiguous behavior (duplicate-address effects).\\n  - The duplicate-IP situation explains why reachability tests between the two hosts reported success: both tests used the same destination IP; responses may come from one of the hosts and the test tool's host-to-IP mapping treated them as the same IP.\\n\\nPotential impacts (observed/likely)\\n- pc_0_0 cannot be reached via its directly-attached leaf/router (local access fails).\\n- IP address conflict may result in intermittent/ambiguous connectivity for 10.0.1.2 services (packets may be delivered to the other host in a different pod).\\n- Normal BGP forwarding causes the fabric to route traffic for the incorrectly-configured IP to the authoritative leaf (leaf_router_0_1), so control-plane and inter-router forwarding behave correctly — the problem is at the host configuration layer.\\n\\nRelevant command outputs (summary references)\\n- pc_0_0 ifconfig: inet 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1\\n- pc_0_1 ifconfig: inet 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1\\n- leaf_router_0_0 eth2: inet 10.0.0.1/24\\n- leaf_router_0_1 eth2: inet 10.0.1.1/24\\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip neigh: no ARP for 10.0.1.2; shows adjacent spines\\n- leaf_router_0_1 -> pc_0_1 ping: success (4/4)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 -> pc_0_0 ping: timed out\\n- BGP tables (all routers): both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 are advertised and present in RIBs.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network fabric (routers, BGP) is functioning normally and propagating the correct /24 advertisements.\\n- The fault is a host configuration error: pc_0_0 is using the wrong IP (10.0.1.2) and gateway, producing a duplicate IP with pc_0_1 and preventing local connectivity via leaf_router_0_0.\\n- Localize the problem to pc_0_0 (host misconfiguration). No router or BGP configuration errors were detected in the data gathered.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- (a) produce a precise list of commands/outputs confirming BGP neighbor/session status, ARP tables on the leaf switch, or packet captures, or\\n- (b) (only if requested) provide recommended corrective steps to fix the misconfiguration., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.\" additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='ab111081-4895-4530-a4f0-d303e873203e'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
